man'; font-size:11pt"> technology</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">function. In the UK only four women lead IT in FTSE 100 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">companies of whom t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">wo are US nationals. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> FTSE 250 only two females are CIOs and three others have senior IT roles but are not leaders of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">function.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is situation is even worse </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">female </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">serving </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">executives in general, at 6% of current FTSE100 and 5% of the FTSE250</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (Source</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> BoardEx</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">While our </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">own </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">database should not be an exhaustive proxy for the total market, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">it nonetheless </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">tells us that of the British nationals we know</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">currently bas</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ed in UK with a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">technology </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">background</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (that is not purely in technology roles), </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">male candidates outweigh female candidates by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ten to one. Looking at all executives on the same database, women represent 15%, which is half as much again. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It is therefore no </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">surprise that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">it is even harder on technology searches </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to come up with long-lists with a balanc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ed set of diversity candidates and progress is slow. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Studying a sample of typical IT/technology searches (including local/regional/global) in 2009</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, we found</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">highest percentage of women on a long-list was 16% (the lowest was 3%) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">whilst </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">today it is 20% (the lowest being 8%).</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Across the wider </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">workplace, the numbers are no</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> more</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> encouraging. Egon Zehnder recently hosted an event with WISE, which promotes and encour</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ages STEM skills in females from “classroom to boardroom” (</span><a href="http://www.wisecampaign.org.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.wisecampaign.org.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">). Their statistics, published earlier this year, show women account for 13% of those in STEM occupations across the UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, barely changed from 12% in 2010. And whilst numbers of women studying science subjects is rising –currently just over half the total at UK universities – this is not necessarily reflected in the workplace. In engineering, for instance, the number of fema</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">le apprentices fell by 10% last year, yet rose for men.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In trying to understand the root causes for these trends we regularly host dinners and are in contact with diversity candidates </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">across our </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">CIO</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">/ CTO</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> network. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">hear </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">that women in particular do not pe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rceive a gender bias</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">; they don’t </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">feel that being female has necessarily held them back in a male-dominated domain. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Nonetheless it is clear to us, from substantial anecdotal </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">comment that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> women </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">may leave or be held back in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the function </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">due to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">deep-seated cu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ltural and behavioural issues.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">For example, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">one </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">senior female technology executive at a leading global IT firm, based in the UK, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">told us s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">chose n</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ot to have a family after watching other women who did have to step back or give up altogether due to the difficulties </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">this </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">involved. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">For her, and perhaps many others, the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> two seemed incompatible. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Another female CIO told us that “self promotion is importan</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t but more of a male thing” whilst women seek to be recognised for the quality of their work: and this also holds them back</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in an environment where asking for a new role and self-advancement </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> expected</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Whilst </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">cultural obstacles</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> are not unique to technol</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ogy, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in any environment with less diversity, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">they are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">likely to be more pronounced. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Egon Zehnder is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">actively working with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">clients and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">other </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">organisations to help address </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">such unconscious biases, but this is likely to be a long process. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">On a more positive </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">note, we also see a new generation of highly capable female technologists emerging from Silicon Valley in the US. Women like Marissa Meyer, now CEO of Yahoo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> or Hearsay Social’s CEO Clara Shih (who also serves on the Starbucks board of directors),</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> are movin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">g beyond the technology function to become leaders at the highest level in the corporate world. This is a trend we see continuing and, with the growth of technology hubs in the UK, potentially being mirrored here as demand grows for tech-savvy leaders. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e wider shift to digital, driving demand for technology skills across all levels of business </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">will </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">help </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">attract more women into the space and to use their skills to rise into broader leadership roles. Egon Zehnder has developed a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n assessment methodology </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">assist this, looking at how an individual’s core traits </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">will </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">lead them to perform in new roles. We believe this is a more accurate predictor of future potential, and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">will</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> help more executives to apply technology skills in new ways. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Whilst there </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">some</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> reason for optimism, the overall picture is challenging. We believe education</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> plays a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">key role and there appears to be a systemic problem rooted in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">early years of school</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and persistent beliefs about “male” and “female” subjects.  A</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> science</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">maths</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> degree is not </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">required </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to become a successful </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">CIO</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">but </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">studying STEM subjects encourages females to pursue technology-related careers.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">M</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ore needs to be done if young women are to achieve their full potential not only in specialist technology careers </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">- </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">but</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> also </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">take their rightful place amongst wider </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">senior management in a more digital </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and technologically advanced </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">world.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>